data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead:

- **`[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`** → constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **`[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`** → a shared **class fixture** via `IClassFixture<T>`

Here's the converted class:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**
- `IClassFixture<T>` — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once and shares it across all tests in the class
- Constructor/`IDisposable` — xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor acts as per-test setup
- `[Fact]` replaces `[Test]`; assertions use `Assert.Equal(expected, actual)` (note: expected comes first)
